body:
While investigating a variant of #59281 and #57517 [reported on Reddit](https://www.reddit.com/r/rust/comments/blv6fn/rustc_optimization_sadness/), I found that even a `while` loop version still had an extra loop that wasn't optimized away. [A minimal example that demonstrates the issue](https://rust.godbolt.org/z/RC02GG):

```
pub fn bongo(num: u32) -> () {
  let mut x = 0;
  while x < num {
    x += 2
  }
}
```

While [the same loop with a step increment of 1 does optimize away the loop](https://rust.godbolt.org/z/cf0kmn):

```
pub fn bongo(num: u32) -> () {
  let mut x = 0;
  while x < num {
    x += 1
  }
}
```

It looks like this optimization happens in `rustc` before LLVM. Increment by 2:

```
; playground::bongo
; Function Attrs: norecurse nounwind nonlazybind readnone uwtable
define void @_ZN10playground5bongo17hf57bf6382d7a4b02E(i32 %num) unnamed_addr #0 {
start:
  br label %bb1

bb1:                                              ; preds = %bb1, %start
  %x.0 = phi i32 [ 0, %start ], [ %1, %bb1 ]
  %0 = icmp ult i32 %x.0, %num
  %1 = add i32 %x.0, 2
  br i1 %0, label %bb1, label %bb2

bb2:                                              ; preds = %bb1
  ret void
}
```

Increment by 1:

```
; playground::bongo
; Function Attrs: norecurse nounwind nonlazybind readnone uwtable
define void @_ZN10playground5bongo17hf57bf6382d7a4b02E(i32 %num) unnamed_addr #0 {
start:
  ret void
}
```
